Let's start by multiplying the factors within and without the square roots:

$\begin{align}
2\sqrt{7x}\cdot 3\sqrt{14x^2}&=2\cdot 3\cdot\sqrt{7x}\cdot\sqrt{14x^2}
\\\\
&=6\sqrt{98x^3}
\end{align}$

Now we remove all perfect squares from inside the square root:

$\begin{align}
6\sqrt{98x^3}&=6\sqrt{7^2\cdot x^2\cdot 2x}
\\\\
&=6\sqrt{7^2}\cdot\sqrt{x^2}\cdot\sqrt{2x}
\\\\
&=6\cdot 7\cdot x\sqrt{2x}
\\\\
&=42x\sqrt{2x}
\end{align}$

Let's start by multiplying the factors within and without the square roots:

$\begin{align}
3\sqrt{5a}\cdot 8\sqrt{35a^2}
&=3\cdot 8\cdot\sqrt{5a}\cdot\sqrt{35a^2}
\\\\
&=24\sqrt{175a^3}
\end{align}$

Now we remove all perfect squares from inside the square root:

$\begin{align}
24\sqrt{175a^3}&=24\sqrt{5^2\cdot a^2\cdot 7a}
\\\\
&=24\sqrt{5^2}\cdot\sqrt{a^2}\cdot\sqrt{7a}
\\\\
&=24\cdot 5\cdot a\sqrt{7a}
\\\\
&=120a\sqrt{7a}
\end{align}$

Let's start by multiplying the factors within and without the square roots:

$\begin{align}
2\sqrt{8b^3}\cdot 9\sqrt{18b}
&=2\cdot 9\cdot\sqrt{8b^3}\cdot\sqrt{18b}
\\\\
&=18\sqrt{144b^4}
\end{align}$

Now we remove all perfect squares from inside the square root:

$\begin{align}
18\sqrt{144b^4}&=18\sqrt{12^2\cdot \left(b^2\right)^2}
\\\\
&=18\sqrt{12^2}\cdot\sqrt{\left(b^2\right)^2}
\\\\
&=18\cdot 12\cdot b^2
\\\\
&=216b^2
\end{align}$

